  <div class="question">
    <h3 id="why-search-results">Why is this site showing up in search results for my name?</h3>
    <p>
      This is a side-effect of the way in which most search engines index content. Somewhere, someone
      has made a web page that links to this site, and that link contains your name (or the link is
      otherwise on a web page that the search engine associates with your name). The search engine
      has therefore assumed that this page contains legitimate information about you (or somebody
      else who shares your name).
    </p>
    <p>
      The same thing would happen, by the way, if a sufficiency of websites contained links to,
      for example, the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idiot">Wikipedia article entitled
      "Idiot"</a> where the text of those links contained or were near to your name, except that
      people searching for your name would find that the top link was the definition of "idiot".
      Where this is done deliberately, it's known as a
      <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Google_bomb">Google bomb</a>.
    </p>
    <p>
      In that case, as in this one, the reason that the link appears in search results is a combination
      of the way in which search engines index content and the frequency with which and the relevance
      rating of <em>other websites</em> that link to this one while using your name. If you want to
      affect those search results, the most-effective way is to have those links removed from
      those other websites: at this point, organic search results - assuming that there is any
      such content associated with your name - will begin to beat this site in listings.
    </p>
  </div>

