  <div class="question">
    <h3 id="why-does-this-exist">Why does this site exist?</h3>
    <p>
      Ever since <a href="https://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec14.html#sec14.23">HTTP/1.1 made the Host header mandatory</a>,
      it's been possible for a web server to know exactly what web address was entered when a compliant
      web browser connects to it. By the early 2000s, HTTP/1.1 had come to be ubiquitous, and servers
      started making significant use of this new feature. Its primary purpose was to allow a web
      server to host many websites, differentiated by name, at a single IP address, but it didn't
      take long for people to combine the Host header with "wildcard DNS", which was well-established
      even before <a href="https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc4592">its formal standardisation</a> in
      2006 in order to allow a web server to host not only a site but also separate sites at each of the
      subdomains of a domain name.
    </p>
    <p>
      A handful of frivilous sites popped up to capitalise on this. Most of these have since fallen
      by the wayside, and those that remain are often either rather homophobic or pretty US-centric.
      I thought that it was time for a new generation of these sites powered by open source software
      and using British slang.
    </p>
  </div>

